i>; see   Cocke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Willcoxon","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcockson","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): patronymic meaning ‘son of   Wilcock  ’."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal name <i>William</i>, <i>Willam</i>, <i>Willem</i>, an Old Picard and Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Willihelm</i>, composed of the elements <i>wil-</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm-</i> ‘helmet, protection’. This Norman personal name became widely used in England, Scotland and Wales after the Conquest, mainly no doubt in honor of the Conqueror himself. By the 13th century it had already become the most popular personal name in England. A Parisian form of the name <i>Guillaume</i> was also sometimes used (see   Gillam  ), which in medieval Wales was adopted as <i>Gwilym</i> (see   Gwilliam  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French   Guillaume  ."]},{"name":"Wilcott","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): habitational name from Willicote in Clifford Chambers (Gloucestershire). The placename derives from Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, hut, shelter’. In some cases perhaps an altered form of   Wilcock  ."]},{"name":"Wilcox","meanings":["English (Yorkshire, Lancashire, and Flintshire): variant of   Wilcock  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This form of the surname is based on the pronunciation."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Wilcock was born in 1247, in Bridgend, Glamorgan, Wales as the daughter of Sir Richard Wilcock I. She married Richard de Turberville in 1255, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1290, in Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1247–1290":"1247–1290","–Female":"Surnud","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1265–1318":"1265–1318","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1200–1285":"1200–1285","1247":"1247","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","Abt 1265":"umbes 1265","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1252":"1252","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1318":"1318","1290":"1290","Coity, Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Bridgend, Glamorgan, Wales":"Bridgend, Glamorgan, Wales","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1247–1290":"1247–1290","–Female":"Kuollut","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1265–1318":"1265–1318","1267–Male":"1267–Kuollut","1200–1285":"1200–1285","1247":"1247","1235":"1235","1267":"1267","1255":"1255","Abt 1265":"noin 1265","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1252":"1252","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","1318":"1318","1290":"1290","Coity, Glamorgan, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bridgend, Glamorgan, Wales":"Bridgend, Glamorgan, Wales","Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Halifax, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1247–1290":"1247–1290","–Female":"Décédée","1235–1283":"1235–1283","1265–1318":"126